<br>
This isn't really true.  There is always room for new businesses, though the types of businesses that thrive at different times vary.  For example, pharmaceuticals manufacturers do quite well in recessions.  There is always room for a new business.  The more new businesses you have, the more new spending you have, which creates need for even more businesses.  The idea that there are a fixed number of jobs in the economy is just silly.  Adding a business creates increases in both the supply and demand curves and balances out.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think the problem is than the defination of &quot;a great many people&quot;. Neither of us have used numbers to back this up. Of course it is very hard to find proper numbers regarding this, because if it was known what people were abusing the system, they wouldn't get wellfare any more. Fact is, it happens. I can only judge this by what I see off this in my environment, which is of course not the broad view you would want. Fact is, it isn't a fundamental problem. Dutch economy was quite healthy in the end of the 90's and even though unemployment rates were a little higher than the US, that is no indication that there is a fundamental problem.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The economy could be healthier if it wasn't giving cash to people that didn't deserve it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think the difference here is, you find it the number of people who choose unemployment unacceptable, I don't. I think I never met somebody who chose to be unemployed (I know they exist though).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Probably true, I find 1 person mooching to be unacceptable.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What makes you think that isn't the case ?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Never said it wasn't.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Of course, that would be taking away jobs from people. Or, if those would be jobs that wouldn't be real jobs anyway, the very fact that you 'create' these jobs would be costing you money.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
See that's where you're wrong.  The thinking that there is a fixed number of jobs out there is the problem, because it's absolutely false.  If you hire these people, they will make money, they will then spend that money and create a need for more jobs.  It's a breakeven.  The same mistake leads to the xenophobia that is so much more present in Europe than in the US.  If you bring an immigrant into this country, and he takes a job, that isn't one less job for Americans.  Sure, he takes a job, but he also spends money.  He buys a house, he buys groceries, he works out at the gym, he watches the game on a big screen TV, he sends his kids to college, etc.  He pumps the money right back into the economy and creates more jobs in the process.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You have to pay those people with those jobs more than standard wellfare OR you have to find these jobs for every single person collecting wellfare.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You find one for every single person.  Even if you didn't you wouldn't have to pay more than standard welfare.  You just make some people work.  If they are on welfare, they have no right to refuse.  If they get lucky and get some time off, good for them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I am all for the principle by the way. But I think it's hard to implement in practice.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It's really not that hard.  You just have to be willing to cut people off when they stop doing their work, even if they have no other source for food.  If someone is not disabled and can work, there is no excuse for them not to work.<br>
